1
00:00:10,865 --> 00:00:14,733
This is flight deck. Prepare the cabin
for Combat Descent into Kandahar.

2
00:00:15,998 --> 00:00:17,336
Excuse me, Dr. Gordon.

3
00:00:17,703 --> 00:00:19,983
I strongly urge you to get
into your seat for landing.

4
00:00:20,103 --> 00:00:23,226
I can't right now,
I'll be out in... 2 minutes.

5
00:00:23,346 --> 00:00:25,079
We're about to do a combat landing, ma'am.

6
00:00:25,199 --> 00:00:27,977
We'll be flying an evasive pattern
so we don't draw fire.

7
00:00:28,097 --> 00:00:30,566
I know what a combat landing is.
I read the manual.

8
00:00:30,686 --> 00:00:34,080
Yes, ma'am. Did the manual say anything
about passengers throwing up?

9
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:35,872
Don't worry about me, I'll be fine.

10
00:00:35,992 --> 00:00:38,078
- Ok.
- Commencing combat descend.

11
00:01:27,513 --> 00:01:36,882
Sync by YYeTs.net
Corrected by Mlmlte
www.addic7ed.com

12
00:01:50,340 --> 00:01:51,930
B.P. 100 over 80.

13
00:01:51,940 --> 00:01:53,520
When did you eat last?

14
00:01:56,520 --> 00:01:57,950
Any drugs you're taking?

15
00:01:58,030 --> 00:01:59,780
Any allergies to medication?

16
00:01:59,800 --> 00:02:02,189
Where are we? Am I gonna die?

17
00:02:02,190 --> 00:02:04,640
You're at the Role 3 Hospital
at Kandahar Airfield,

18
00:02:05,910 --> 00:02:07,350
and you're gonna be fine.

19
00:02:18,650 --> 00:02:19,640
Excuse me. Ma'am?

20
00:02:19,650 --> 00:02:21,120
I'm looking for the Role 3 Multinatio--

21
00:02:21,121 --> 00:02:23,479
Multinational Medical Unit. Yeah. Me, too.

22
00:02:23,480 --> 00:02:25,139
Hi, I'm Bobby Trang.

23
00:02:25,140 --> 00:02:27,469
Nice to meet you. Rebecca Gordon. 
Hi, Rebecca.

24
00:02:27,470 --> 00:02:29,150
So one of us is walking the wrong way.

25
00:02:29,151 --> 00:02:31,109
Uh, I just got directions,

26
00:02:31,110 --> 00:02:34,170
and apparently, it is this way.

27
00:02:36,590 --> 00:02:38,609
I'm sorry. I'm not familiar
with Canadian ranks.

28
00:02:38,610 --> 00:02:41,639
I'm a major and trauma surgeon. You?

29
00:02:41,640 --> 00:02:44,220
Brand-new captain and a brand-new doctor.

30
00:02:45,300 --> 00:02:46,700
Oh, excuse me.

31
00:02:47,320 --> 00:02:48,750
Excuse me. Can you--

32
00:02:51,770 --> 00:02:53,790
Lewis, take point!

33
00:02:55,200 --> 00:02:56,440
That was weird.

34
00:02:58,020 --> 00:02:59,270
So you're a major?

35
00:03:01,050 --> 00:03:02,220
Is that you?

36
00:03:03,310 --> 00:03:04,730
You get reception out here?

37
00:03:05,890 --> 00:03:09,750
Damn it. Yeah, I got nothing--
no bars, no messages, nada.

38
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:11,980
You're not even gonna read them?

39
00:03:12,840 --> 00:03:15,720
No. They're from my ex.
He's turned into a stalker.

40
00:03:19,180 --> 00:03:21,380
Excuse me for asking, but
are you feeling okay?

41
00:03:21,930 --> 00:03:23,110
I'm fine.

42
00:03:23,790 --> 00:03:24,960
I'm fine.

43
00:03:25,370 --> 00:03:28,330
I'm just tired.
I don't sleep well on planes.

44
00:03:28,920 --> 00:03:32,000
It's nothing that a solid eight
hours of sleep won't cure.

45
00:03:35,360 --> 00:03:36,650
How's it going, Simon?

46
00:03:36,850 --> 00:03:39,170
Piece of cake, Colonel.

47
00:03:39,670 --> 00:03:41,680
Any sign of our fresh meat?

48
00:03:41,910 --> 00:03:44,410
Nice way to refer to
your future colleagues.

49
00:03:45,980 --> 00:03:48,169
Let's see how long they last.

50
00:03:48,170 --> 00:03:51,429
We have to find them first.
They're lost in transit.

51
00:03:51,430 --> 00:03:54,529
Well, if they knew what was
coming, they'd stay lost.

52
00:03:54,530 --> 00:03:55,520
We need the manpower, Simon.

53
00:03:55,521 --> 00:03:58,100
Really? I'd say we need more women.

54
00:03:59,180 --> 00:04:02,009
Actually-- one of them is.

55
00:04:02,010 --> 00:04:04,040
Oh, really? Now you're talking.

56
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:14,520
Well, I don't know what I was picturing,

57
00:04:15,190 --> 00:04:16,190
but-- it wasn't this.

58
00:04:16,191 --> 00:04:17,860
No. That's for sure.

59
00:04:19,100 --> 00:04:20,560
I hope they have air conditioning.

60
00:04:20,561 --> 00:04:21,660
Yeah, right? 
Whew.

61
00:04:46,510 --> 00:04:47,660
Outpatient clinic is closed.

62
00:04:47,661 --> 00:04:49,640
Just take a seat.
We'll see you as soon as we can.

63
00:04:50,590 --> 00:04:53,600
Oh, no. We're not sick.
We're reporting for duty.

64
00:04:53,790 --> 00:04:56,180
Oh, I'm sorry.
It's just that you looked a little--

65
00:04:56,870 --> 00:04:58,100
You know what? Never mind. We can use you.

66
00:04:58,101 --> 00:04:59,900
We just had a rush.
We're about to have another one.

67
00:05:00,510 --> 00:05:02,609
Okay, listen, clean the blood off the floor

68
00:05:02,610 --> 00:05:04,040
so that no one slips, okay?

69
00:05:04,041 --> 00:05:06,019
Oh, you don't understand.

70
00:05:06,020 --> 00:05:07,689
Um, we're doctors. 
What?

71
00:05:07,690 --> 00:05:09,820
Does that mean we have to show
you how to mop the floor?

72
00:05:10,470 --> 00:05:12,840
No, no. I know how to mop a floor.

73
00:05:12,870 --> 00:05:14,410
Great. I just think that may--

74
00:05:14,870 --> 00:05:16,670
I'm going to reload these.

75
00:05:17,090 --> 00:05:19,650
I guess we mop the floor.
I guess so.

76
00:05:22,340 --> 00:05:23,670
Okay, who left their damn bags

77
00:05:23,671 --> 00:05:26,400
right in the middle of the floor?
Sorry, sir. We just got in.

78
00:05:27,370 --> 00:05:29,840
Uh-huh. Captain Trang. 
Yes, Major Gordon.

79
00:05:30,100 --> 00:05:31,919
We were expecting you yesterday.

80
00:05:31,920 --> 00:05:34,090
I got stuck in Dubai. I got stuck in Kabul.

81
00:05:34,100 --> 00:05:36,699
Any updates?
Dust-off 1-7's five minutes out, sir.

82
00:05:36,700 --> 00:05:38,920
Dust-off 2-2 is right behind
them with four on board,

83
00:05:38,921 --> 00:05:41,570
no details, TOC's only getting
every second word, sir.

84
00:05:42,960 --> 00:05:45,020
Who are they?
This is Major Gordon, Captain Trang, sir,

85
00:05:45,021 --> 00:05:46,940
reporting for duty.
We were expecting you yesterday.

86
00:05:46,941 --> 00:05:48,360
Sorry, sir. We both, uh, got--

87
00:05:48,361 --> 00:05:50,310
Don't tell me. Dubai.

88
00:05:51,610 --> 00:05:52,650
You feeling all right?

89
00:05:54,210 --> 00:05:56,310
Absolutely, sir. 
Yeah. I'm good to go.

90
00:05:56,320 --> 00:05:57,670
All right. Follow me.

91
00:05:59,670 --> 00:06:00,640
All right.

92
00:06:00,641 --> 00:06:03,990
Now we got recovery and I.C.U. here.

93
00:06:04,270 --> 00:06:06,110
Sorry we gotta put you to
work the minute you get here,

94
00:06:06,111 --> 00:06:08,540
but, you'll find this place
very unlike anything--

95
00:06:08,541 --> 00:06:09,960
you ever experienced before.

96
00:06:09,980 --> 00:06:12,420
Now we go three O.R.s here.

97
00:06:12,970 --> 00:06:15,769
The main ward's down the hall at the end.

98
00:06:15,770 --> 00:06:17,659
Uh, actually, Colonel, um,

99
00:06:17,660 --> 00:06:19,120
I trained at both Detroit receiving

100
00:06:19,130 --> 00:06:20,630
and Miami General, and we could see,

101
00:06:20,631 --> 00:06:21,390
four, five, -- I don't doubt it.

102
00:06:21,391 --> 00:06:23,510
Even six-- we got mental health right here.

103
00:06:23,650 --> 00:06:25,480
Down here's the central hallway.

104
00:06:26,510 --> 00:06:30,230
And here--the U.S. Army
used to call this the ready room.

105
00:06:31,880 --> 00:06:33,470
I haven't been able to
come up with another name.

106
00:06:33,471 --> 00:06:35,080
The unready room, I call it.

107
00:06:35,860 --> 00:06:37,050
Hey.

108
00:06:39,420 --> 00:06:41,130
Well, hello.

109
00:06:41,990 --> 00:06:43,800
This is Dr. Hill, our neurosurgeon.

110
00:06:44,980 --> 00:06:46,140
Please, call me Simon.

111
00:06:46,141 --> 00:06:48,379
I'm Rebecca. 
Hey, man. I'm Bobby.

112
00:06:48,380 --> 00:06:49,680
Hello, Bobby.

113
00:06:50,490 --> 00:06:52,450
You can change into your scrubs in there.

114
00:06:52,810 --> 00:06:54,050
Just the shirt.

115
00:06:55,540 --> 00:06:58,330
Now you can store your firearms
in these lockers if you want to.

116
00:06:58,370 --> 00:07:00,900
I wear mine because I'm
always going in and out.

117
00:07:01,230 --> 00:07:03,289
And besides, I like the constant reminder

118
00:07:03,290 --> 00:07:04,710
that we're in a war zone.

119
00:07:04,711 --> 00:07:07,159
Sir, two minutes out. 
New details?

120
00:07:07,160 --> 00:07:08,080
Yes, sir.

121
00:07:08,810 --> 00:07:12,370
So did they, uh, did they
try to hand you a mop?

122
00:07:12,930 --> 00:07:15,009
They didn't just try. They succeeded.

123
00:07:15,010 --> 00:07:16,500
Oh, they tried that with me.
They didn't get very far.

124
00:07:16,501 --> 00:07:17,770
Let me tell you.

125
00:07:18,640 --> 00:07:19,810
Yes, sir.

126
00:07:21,800 --> 00:07:23,000
Sir.

127
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:25,220
You have emergency
medicine training, right?

128
00:07:25,221 --> 00:07:27,329
Yes, sir, but just the standard 3-month--

129
00:07:27,330 --> 00:07:30,450
Good. You're trauma team
leader, bay 4, all right?

130
00:07:31,890 --> 00:07:32,720
Ready, sir.

131
00:07:32,730 --> 00:07:36,549
Let's go. You, too, Simon.
Right behind you, Colonel.

132
00:07:36,550 --> 00:07:39,420
To be honest with you, sir, I've
never been a T.T.L. before.

133
00:07:39,490 --> 00:07:41,060
I like to think I'm a good diagnostician,

134
00:07:41,061 --> 00:07:42,190
but you know your ABC's, don't you?

135
00:07:42,191 --> 00:07:44,420
Airway, breathing, circulation.
So you'll be fine.

136
00:07:44,421 --> 00:07:45,990
Uh, I have tons of T.T.L. experience.

137
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:47,550
No, I want to leave you free for surgery.

138
00:07:47,551 --> 00:07:50,770
Until then, stand by the red line
in case someone needs your help.

139
00:07:54,990 --> 00:07:57,169
All right. They're here. Let's go!

140
00:07:57,170 --> 00:07:59,079
Bird landing any second!

141
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:01,370
All right. Trauma bay 4, doctor. This way.

142
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:04,660
All right, everyone.
I'd like you to meet Dr. Bobby Trang.

143
00:08:04,740 --> 00:08:06,200
This is Captain Pam Everwood, your nurse.

144
00:08:06,201 --> 00:08:07,010
These are your med techs,

145
00:08:07,011 --> 00:08:08,740
Larry Alexander and Christine Ezrin.

146
00:08:08,741 --> 00:08:10,620
You okay? 
Yeah.

147
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:12,220
Don't worry about it. They got your back.

148
00:08:12,221 --> 00:08:15,050
You're gonna need this.
Okay, everyone, let's go!

149
00:08:25,280 --> 00:08:28,430
G.C.S. 9, B.P. 100 over 40. Pulse 102.

150
00:08:28,480 --> 00:08:31,680
Labored breathing. I.E.D.
blast 5-0 minutes ago.

151
00:08:33,230 --> 00:08:34,679
G.C.S. 9--should, uh,

152
00:08:34,680 --> 00:08:36,790
should we tube him? 
Your call, Doctor.

153
00:08:38,380 --> 00:08:40,590
Shallow breathing.
I'm getting nothing on the right side.

154
00:08:40,591 --> 00:08:43,260
Let's try some adrenaline. B.P. falling.

155
00:08:49,440 --> 00:08:50,950
Okay. We'll tube him.

156
00:08:51,020 --> 00:08:54,800
Can I get a-- B.P. falling. 75 over 20.

157
00:08:55,630 --> 00:08:58,280
20 of etimodate and 100 of sux.
Given.

158
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:01,450
Can I get a smaller tube?

159
00:09:01,790 --> 00:09:03,590
Do you want more blood, Doctor? 
Yeah.

160
00:09:03,591 --> 00:09:06,340
O neg. O-2 sat 93% and falling.

161
00:09:06,440 --> 00:09:09,590
Damn it. Get in there.
Blood pressure's dropping fast, doctor.

162
00:09:13,820 --> 00:09:15,540
Get in there.

163
00:09:17,050 --> 00:09:18,510
Want some help with that airway, doctor?

164
00:09:18,511 --> 00:09:20,120
Yes, please, sir.

165
00:09:28,090 --> 00:09:29,220
Stylet out.

166
00:09:31,190 --> 00:09:32,700
It's in the right place. 
Bag him.

167
00:09:35,510 --> 00:09:37,700
Shallow on the left.
Still nothing on the right.

168
00:09:48,400 --> 00:09:49,660
Chest tube.

169
00:09:58,880 --> 00:10:01,540
That got it. I'm getting
bilateral breath sounds now.

170
00:10:02,150 --> 00:10:04,950
O-2 sat 95% and rising.

171
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:07,270
Do you want to get him to the O.R., sir?

172
00:10:08,800 --> 00:10:10,090
Doctor, what would you like?

173
00:10:17,660 --> 00:10:19,000
Whatever you say, sir.

174
00:10:49,380 --> 00:10:51,400
No, don't get up just yet, son.

175
00:10:52,290 --> 00:10:54,180
I'm Commander Royal, your nurse.

176
00:10:54,330 --> 00:10:55,940
Everything's gonna be fine.

177
00:10:57,390 --> 00:11:00,710
Do I-- 
Yeah, you've got your arms and your legs,

178
00:11:00,880 --> 00:11:02,240
and everything you had yesterday,

179
00:11:02,241 --> 00:11:04,329
including some ugly looking plastic tubes

180
00:11:04,330 --> 00:11:05,580
sticking out of your chest,

181
00:11:05,581 --> 00:11:08,040
which we gotta keep in for a few more days.

182
00:11:09,820 --> 00:11:12,550
Mm. Yeah, your ribs are gonna
be sore for a bit, so--

183
00:11:12,690 --> 00:11:16,000
you in any pain at all?
No, sir. Not really.

184
00:11:16,330 --> 00:11:19,030
Well, you speak up if there's
anything that you need.

185
00:11:19,450 --> 00:11:20,580
Anything at all.

186
00:11:24,040 --> 00:11:25,400
Welcome back, soldier.

187
00:11:26,080 --> 00:11:29,470
I'm Dr. Marks. 
You missed your C.O. by half an hour.

188
00:11:30,380 --> 00:11:31,870
He left you a purple heart.

189
00:11:32,870 --> 00:11:34,940
Your unit chaplain's got a satellite
phone so you could call home.

190
00:11:36,820 --> 00:11:38,290
Your buddies are in the waiting room.

191
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:42,660
Thank you, sirs, both of you.

192
00:11:42,930 --> 00:11:43,790
You don't have to thank us.

193
00:11:43,791 --> 00:11:45,960
We're just the guys that get
to give you the good news.

194
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:51,049
Aha. There you are.
I have your orientation packets.

195
00:11:51,050 --> 00:11:52,900
They have your room
assignments and your keys.

196
00:11:52,901 --> 00:11:55,120
I also had your bags sent over already.

197
00:11:55,270 --> 00:11:58,099
You are to wear these at all times.

198
00:11:58,100 --> 00:12:01,199
The code 9-1-1 means drop
whatever it is you're doing

199
00:12:01,200 --> 00:12:04,079
and get here quick. 
Beepers in 2006?

200
00:12:04,080 --> 00:12:05,759
Old-fashioned, but reliable.

201
00:12:05,760 --> 00:12:08,090
Which reminds me, Major, you
got a personal e-mail message

202
00:12:08,091 --> 00:12:09,669
sent via the D.N.D. in Ottawa.

203
00:12:09,670 --> 00:12:11,150
You'll notice that you have your own

204
00:12:11,160 --> 00:12:13,829
individual e-mail addresses
in your folders.

205
00:12:13,830 --> 00:12:15,920
If you could ask your friend to
use that one in the future--

206
00:12:15,970 --> 00:12:16,970
Uh, if he does it again,

207
00:12:16,971 --> 00:12:18,620
Just please tell him to eat crap and die.

208
00:12:18,621 --> 00:12:20,710
"Eat crap and die." 
Yes, ma'am.

209
00:12:22,140 --> 00:12:24,829
Oh, got 'em all sorted out?

210
00:12:24,830 --> 00:12:26,989
Yes, sir. Fine additions
to the team they are,

211
00:12:26,990 --> 00:12:27,960
if I may say so myself, sir.

212
00:12:28,200 --> 00:12:30,090
You may. I couldn't agree more.

213
00:12:34,610 --> 00:12:35,830
Walk with me.

214
00:12:38,380 --> 00:12:39,830
Did somebody die without telling me?

215
00:12:39,831 --> 00:12:40,450
No, sir.

216
00:12:40,451 --> 00:12:41,790
No, nobody died.

217
00:12:43,770 --> 00:12:46,110
When he came into your trauma
bay, he was dying, no question,

218
00:12:46,300 --> 00:12:47,639
but he went out alive.

219
00:12:47,640 --> 00:12:52,410
And there he is-- P.F.C.
George Lowen, 19, from Dayton, Ohio,

220
00:12:52,860 --> 00:12:55,320
and he's about to make a
call to his mom and dad.

221
00:12:55,720 --> 00:12:56,800
All right?

222
00:12:57,020 --> 00:12:59,640
I couldn't think, sir.
I-I couldn't even fit the tube in.

223
00:13:00,310 --> 00:13:02,889
Well, that kid had the biggest
damn uvula I've ever seen.

224
00:13:02,890 --> 00:13:04,280
You didn't have any trouble with it.

225
00:13:05,180 --> 00:13:07,130
I've been doing it for 25 years.

226
00:13:09,950 --> 00:13:11,880
You know what the most
important thing-- oh.

227
00:13:11,881 --> 00:13:13,180
Sorry if I scared you.

228
00:13:13,181 --> 00:13:15,290
You didn't scare me. You startled me.

229
00:13:15,340 --> 00:13:17,620
Ah. Well, I stand corrected.

230
00:13:18,380 --> 00:13:21,289
That's a nice, uh, tattoo you got there.
Yes, sir.

231
00:13:21,290 --> 00:13:25,150
Oh, come on. No, I mean it sincerely.
A sincere compliment.

232
00:13:25,260 --> 00:13:27,730
Simon, you mind if I cut in?

233
00:13:27,770 --> 00:13:29,430
Yes, of course, Colonel.

234
00:13:29,710 --> 00:13:33,780
I will be in the unready
room, getting unready.

235
00:13:35,400 --> 00:13:37,440
You did a very good job
with the chest tube today.

236
00:13:37,441 --> 00:13:38,380
Thank you, sir.

237
00:13:39,120 --> 00:13:42,709
How well do you know Bobby Trang?
Uh, we only just met.

238
00:13:42,710 --> 00:13:45,130
So you've got nothing against him?
No, of course not.

239
00:13:45,330 --> 00:13:48,140
Well, you completely undermined his
confidence by stepping in like that.

240
00:13:48,350 --> 00:13:52,499
Me? Sir, I didn't do
anything before you did.

241
00:13:52,500 --> 00:13:55,200
No, I asked permission. You took over.
There's a big difference.

242
00:13:56,820 --> 00:13:59,730
- You didn't see that line of red tape
on the floor? - Yes, sir.

243
00:14:00,870 --> 00:14:01,880
You know what it means?
No one crosses the red line.

244
00:14:01,881 --> 00:14:04,170
Unless? 
Unless instructed by the trauma team leader.

245
00:14:04,171 --> 00:14:06,379
Exactly. 
Sir, the patient was tanking--

246
00:14:06,380 --> 00:14:07,680
No, he'd would've survived another minute,

247
